Classification Project¶

Problem Statement¶

Hypothesis¶

Null hypothesis:

The model is significantly able to classify a customer as an individual who is likely to purchase a healthy product.

Alternative hypothesis:

The model is significantly unable to classify a customer as an individual who is likely to purchase a healthy product.

The significant level will be when the r coefficient is higher than 0.5 or lower than -0.5 and the p-value lower than 0.05.

Overview¶

The initial plan for the project is as follows:

  1. Source the data
  2. Explore & clean the data
  3. Prepare the data for analysis
  4. Analyse the data
  5. Evaluate the model
  6. Improve the model

Source the data¶

The data was sourced from two sources. The first source was from our enterprise analytics hub where customer transactional data was collected. Unfortunately, I was not able to connect directly to EAH, so I forced to write a SQL statement is Impala and to export the dataset in a CSV. The second source was the Health attribute data set which is a small data set that was manually maintained in excel.

Potential issues with the data, as transactional data can be quite huge, I decided for practicality that I will only export one months’ worth of data. I personally believe this may not be enough data for the model to use to be able to make a good prediction. The second issue is that the health attribute data has not been maintained since March 2019. The potential issue only a small fraction of those products may still be in our catalogue affecting the true frequency of the current amount of health products being purchased.

In terms of sharing issues, we must be very careful when dealing with customer data as this is considered private and sensitive data even though no personal data is present such as names or addresses. We also need to consider how we communicate and present the data when dealing with gender and age as these are also sensitive topics as we do not wish to present ourselves as misusing customer data.

Explore & clean the data¶

Initially the idea was to explore, clean and then prepare the data but due to issue while exploring It was decided to merge the exploring and the cleaning process into one.

As we can see the accuracy score is 100% but this isn’t desirable and usually isn’t obtainable, this means that our model is potentially over fitted.

In [407]:
# y_test is a dataframe and to use the function confusion_matrix it is necessary to convert y_test to a list
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
y_true = y_test.tolist()
mat = confusion_matrix(y_true,y_pred)
sns.heatmap(mat.T, square =True, annot = True, fmt = 'd', cbar= False)
plt.xlabel('True data')
plt.ylabel('predicted values')
Out[407]:
Text(91.68, 0.5, 'predicted values')

From the confusion matrix above we can see that for 0 a count of 9168 true positives and 0 false positive predictions which means no customer who did not purchase a healthy product was labelled as a healthy buyer. We can also see for 1 a count of 0 true positive and 23 false negatives, which means all customers who bought a healthy product were labelled as non-healthy buyers. The reason is for the sheer volume of non healthy buyers in compariosn to healthy buyers. In this case our calssifier classified all our robservations as non healthy buyers due to 100% recognition rate (sensitivity) for non healthy buyers class and a 0% for healthy buyer class.

Out[410]:

After creating our model, we can conclude that it was potentially overfitted as it had a very high accuracy rate of 99.7%. We could not find any variables with a significant correlation with the healthy indicator either. The model was able to predict every observation correctly for customers who did not buy a healthy product but was unable to predict one single observation correct for a customer who did purchase a healthy product. We do understand that is due to unproportioned dataset which was heavily weighted towards customers who did not buy a healthy product.

This means my concerns outlined in the source the data section seems to have been cemented as the out of date data for the healthy products means a lot of products currently healthy are not in the list.

This means we must reject the null hypothesis that the model is significantly able to classify a customer as an individual who is likely to purchase a healthy product. As a result, we must then accept our alternative hypothesis which is the model is significantly unable to classify a customer as an individual who is likely to purchase a healthy product.

I believe if all the concerns outlined in the source the data are addressed and possibly selecting better variables it could be possible to create a function model that will be able to significantly determine if a customer will purchase a healthy product.
